A Risk Management Program (RMP) has been developed and a Risk Management Plan (hereafter referred to as ?the Plan?) has been prepared for use and storage of anhydrous ammonia in the Nash Finch Company (Cedar Rapids, Iowa facility) refrigeration system. The RMP and the Plan meet and address the requirements of Title 40 Code of Federal Regulations Part 68.

This executive summary briefly describes the following elements: 

?The stationary source and regulated substances handled; 
?The accidental release prevention and emergency response policies at the stationary source; 
?The worst-case release scenario(s) and the alternative release scenario(s), including administrative controls and mitigation measures to limit the distances for each reported scenario; 
?The five-year accident history; 
?The general accidental release prevention program and chemical-specific prevention steps; 
?The emergency response program; and 
?Planned changes to improve safety. 

Anhydrous ammonia is used as a refrigerant in the Nash Finch Company (Cedar Rapids, Iowa facility) refrigeration system. The liquid is circulated as needed to the evaporators where heat is absorbed and removed from the medium. The anhydrous ammonia refrigeration system is a closed loop industrial refrigeration system. The ammonia is not used or mixed in any manner with other chemical processes. 

To address concerns of an accidental release prevention and emergency response, all plant and field personnel are trained in ammonia emergency response procedures and use of appropriate protective equipment. Refresher training and emergency response drills are conducted on a periodic basis to ensure personnel are equipped, trained, prepared, and practiced in responding to ammonia emergencies. 

A ?Worst-Case Scenario Offsite Consequence Analysis? and an ?Alternative Scenario Offsite Consequence Analysis? were performed identifying the public and environmental receptors within the toxic endpoint concentration radius of 200 ppm.
